msgid "LLVM intrinsic call"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:0
msgid "LLVM already has a built-in for it"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:0
msgid "`threadIdx_x`, warp shuffles, barriers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:0
msgid "Inline PTX assembly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:0
msgid ""
"No LLVM intrinsic exists, or you need exact control over the PTX instruction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:0
msgid "`trap`, `wgmma`, `tcgen05`, `mbarrier`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:41
msgid "Both strategies are demonstrated below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:45
msgid "Example 1: `threadIdx_x` (the Simple Case)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:47
msgid ""
"`threadIdx_x()` is the \"Hello, World\" of GPU intrinsics: zero arguments, "
"one `u32` result, maps directly to a single LLVM NVVM intrinsic. If you can "
"follow this example, you can add any simple intrinsic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:51
#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:227
msgid "Stage 1 -- Declare in `cuda-device`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:53
msgid "**File:** `crates/cuda-device/src/thread.rs`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:55
msgid ""
"#[inline(never)]\n"
"pub fn threadIdx_x() -> u32 {\n"
"    unreachable!(\"threadIdx_x called outside CUDA kernel context\")\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:62
msgid "Two rules that might look odd until you understand the trick:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:64
msgid ""
"**`#[inline(never)]`** keeps the function visible as a distinct call in MIR. "
"If rustc inlined it, the compiler would see `unreachable!()` instead of a "
"call it can intercept. That would be... less than helpful."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:68
msgid ""
"**The body is `unreachable!()`** because this function never actually runs. "
"The compiler replaces the entire call with a `dialect-nvvm` operation before "
"any GPU code executes. Think of the function as a placeholder -- a \"dear "
"compiler, please insert a GPU instruction here\" note."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:74
msgid ""
"Document what LLVM IR or PTX the intrinsic maps to in a comment above the "
"function. Future you (or future contributors) will thank present you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:78
#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:242
msgid "Stage 2 -- Define the `dialect-nvvm` Op"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:80
msgid "**File:** `crates/dialect-nvvm/src/ops/thread.rs`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:82
msgid ""
"#[pliron_op(name = \"nvvm.read_ptx_sreg_tid_x\", dialect = \"nvvm\", "
"format)]\n"
"pub struct ReadPtxSregTidXOp;\n"
"\n"
"impl Verify for ReadPtxSregTidXOp {\n"
"    fn verify(&self, ctx: &Context) -> Result<(), Error> {\n"
"        let op = &*self.get_operation().deref(ctx);\n"
"        if op.get_num_operands() != 0 {\n"
"            return verify_err!(op.loc(), \"expected 0 operands\");\n"
"        }\n"
"        if op.get_num_results() != 1 {\n"
"            return verify_err!(op.loc(), \"expected 1 result\");\n"
"        }\n"
"        Ok(())\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:100
msgid "Then register it so pliron knows the op exists:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:102
msgid ""
"pub(super) fn register(ctx: &mut Context) {\n"
"    ReadPtxSregTidXOp::register(ctx, ReadPtxSregTidXOp::parser_fn);\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:108
msgid ""
"The `Verify` trait catches structural bugs early. If something accidentally "
"creates this op with two operands, verification fails with a clear message "
"instead of producing garbage PTX three stages later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:112
#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:266
msgid "Stage 3 -- Recognize in `mir-importer`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:114
#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:268
msgid "**File:** `crates/mir-importer/src/translator/terminator/mod.rs`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:116
msgid ""
"When the translator processes MIR, every function call passes through "
"`try_dispatch_intrinsic()`. The callee's fully qualified domain name (FQDN) "
"comes from `CrateDef::name()` via `extract_func_info()`, producing paths "
"like `cuda_device::thread::threadIdx_x`. The match checks this FQDN:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:121
msgid ""
"match name {\n"
"    \"cuda_device::threadIdx_x\" | \"cuda_device::thread::threadIdx_x\" => "
"{\n"
"        Ok(Some(helpers::emit_nvvm_intrinsic(\n"
"            ctx,\n"
"            ReadPtxSregTidXOp::get_concrete_op_info(),\n"
"            destination, target, block_ptr, prev_op,\n"
"            value_map, block_map, loc,\n"
"        )?))\n"
"    }\n"
"    // ... hundreds of other intrinsics ...\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:135
msgid ""
"We match both the re-exported name (`cuda_device::threadIdx_x`) and the full "
"module path (`cuda_device::thread::threadIdx_x`) so both work regardless of "
"how the user imports the function. The FQDN is used as-is for matching -- no "
"`::` to `__` conversion happens before the intrinsic check."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:140
msgid ""
"The `emit_nvvm_intrinsic()` helper is a generic function that works for "
"*any* zero-argument, single-result NVVM intrinsic. It creates the operation, "
"stores the result in the value map, and emits a branch to the next basic "
"block. For simple intrinsics, you never need to write a custom emitter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:145
#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:308
msgid "Stage 4 -- Lower to the LLVM dialect"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:147
msgid "**File:** `crates/mir-lower/src/convert/intrinsics/basic.rs`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:149
msgid ""
"The op implements the `MirToLlvmConversion` op interface. In `convert/"
"interface_impls.rs`, the impl dispatches to a converter function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:152
msgid ""
"impl MirToLlvmConversion for ReadPtxSregTidXOp {\n"
"    fn rewrite(ctx, rewriter, op, operands_info) -> Result<()> {\n"
"        basic::convert_read_tid_x(ctx, rewriter, op, operands_info)\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:160
msgid "Then `basic::convert_read_tid_x` emits the LLVM intrinsic call:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:162
msgid ""
"pub fn convert_read_tid_x(\n"
"    ctx: &mut Context,\n"
"    rewriter: &mut DialectConversionRewriter,\n"
"    op: Ptr<Operation>,\n"
"    _operands_info: &OperandsInfo,\n"
") -> Result<()> {\n"
"    let intrinsic_name = \"llvm_nvvm_read_ptx_sreg_tid_x\";\n"
"    let i32_ty = IntegerType::get(ctx, 32, Signedness::Signless);\n"
"    let func_ty = FuncType::get(ctx, i32_ty.into(), vec![], false);\n"
"\n"
"    let call_op = call_intrinsic(ctx, rewriter, intrinsic_name, func_ty, vec!"
"[])?;\n"
"    rewriter.replace_operation_with_values(ctx, op, vec![result]);\n"
"    Ok(())\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:180
msgid ""
"LLVM intrinsic names use dots (`llvm.nvvm.read.ptx.sreg.tid.x`), but pliron "
"identifiers cannot contain dots. Internally we use underscores "
"(`llvm_nvvm_read_ptx_sreg_tid_x`). The export stage converts them back."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:185
msgid "Stage 5 -- Export (Nothing to Change)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:187
msgid "**File:** `crates/llvm-export/src/export/` (the export module)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:189
msgid "The `CallOp` exporter already handles the underscore-to-dot conversion:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:191
msgid ""
"let fixed_name = if name.starts_with(\"llvm_nvvm\") {\n"
"    name.replace('_', \".\")\n"
"} else {\n"
"    strip_device_prefix(&name)\n"
"};\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:199
msgid ""
"Since `threadIdx_x` is *not* convergent (it is a per-thread register read, "
"not a collective operation), there is nothing to add to "
"`is_convergent_intrinsic()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:203
#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:367
msgid "**Final output:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:205
msgid ""
"declare i32 @llvm.nvvm.read.ptx.sreg.tid.x()\n"
"%v5 = call i32 @llvm.nvvm.read.ptx.sreg.tid.x()\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:210
#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:378
msgid "After `llc`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:212
msgid "mov.u32  %r1, %tid.x;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:216
msgid "Five stages, one PTX instruction. Not bad."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:220
msgid "Example 2: `shuffle_xor` (the Complex Case)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:222
msgid ""
"Warp shuffles are more interesting. The user passes two arguments, but the "
"underlying LLVM intrinsic expects *four*. The compiler quietly fills in the "
"extras. The operation is also **convergent**, meaning LLVM must not move, "
"duplicate, or speculate it across control flow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:229
msgid "**File:** `crates/cuda-device/src/warp.rs`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:231
msgid ""
"#[inline(never)]\n"
"pub fn shuffle_xor(var: u32, lane_mask: u32) -> u32 {\n"
"    let _ = (var, lane_mask);\n"
"    unreachable!(\"shuffle_xor called outside CUDA kernel context\")\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:239
msgid ""
"Same pattern as before. The `let _ = (var, lane_mask);` suppresses unused-"
"variable warnings -- a small courtesy that costs nothing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:244
msgid "**File:** `crates/dialect-nvvm/src/ops/warp.rs`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:246
msgid ""
"#[pliron_op(name = \"nvvm.shfl_sync_bfly_i32\", dialect = \"nvvm\", "
"format)]\n"
"pub struct ShflSyncBflyI32Op;\n"
"\n"
"impl Verify for ShflSyncBflyI32Op {\n"
"    fn verify(&self, ctx: &Context) -> Result<(), Error> {\n"
"        let op = &*self.get_operation().deref(ctx);\n"
"        if op.get_num_operands() != 2 {\n"
"            return verify_err!(op.loc(), \"expected 2 operands\");\n"
"        }\n"
"        if op.get_num_results() != 1 {\n"
"            return verify_err!(op.loc(), \"expected 1 result\");\n"
"        }\n"
"        Ok(())\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:264
msgid "Two operands this time (value and lane mask), one result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:270
msgid ""
"Unlike `threadIdx_x`, this calls a **specialized emitter** because it needs "
"to handle the user's two arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:273
msgid ""
"\"cuda_device::warp::shuffle_xor\" => Ok(Some(\n"
"    intrinsics::warp::emit_warp_shuffle_i32(\n"
"        ctx, body,\n"
"        ShflSyncBflyI32Op::get_concrete_op_info(),\n"
"        args, destination, target, ...\n"
"    )?\n"
")),\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:283
msgid ""
"**File:** `crates/mir-importer/src/translator/terminator/intrinsics/warp.rs`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:285
msgid ""
"pub fn emit_warp_shuffle_i32(ctx, body, shuffle_opid, args, ...) {\n"
"    if args.len() != 2 { return error; }\n"
"\n"
"    let (val, _) = translate_operand(ctx, body, &args[0], ...);\n"
"    let (lane_or_mask, _) = translate_operand(ctx, body, &args[1], ...);\n"
"\n"
"    let shuffle_op = Operation::new(ctx, shuffle_opid,\n"
"        vec![u32_type.to_ptr()],          // results: [u32]\n"
"        vec![val, lane_or_mask],          // operands: [value, mask]\n"
"        vec![], 0,\n"
"    );\n"
"\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:301
msgid ""
"The emitter translates the user's MIR operands into pliron values -- "
"typically the results of `mir.load`s from each operand's alloca slot, or "
"`mir.constant`s for literal arguments -- and wires them into the NVVM "
"operation. (These are not SSA values yet; `pliron::opts::mem2reg` will "
"collapse the load/store chains once translation is complete.) For intrinsics "
"with different argument patterns, you write a similar custom emitter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:310
msgid "**File:** `crates/mir-lower/src/convert/intrinsics/warp.rs`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:312
msgid ""
"Here is where it gets interesting. The LLVM intrinsic for butterfly shuffle "
"takes **four** arguments, not two:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:315
msgid ""
"User's API:     shuffle_xor(value, lane_mask)            →  2 args\n"
"LLVM intrinsic: shfl.sync.bfly.i32(mask, value, lane_mask, clamp) →  4 args\n"
"                                    ^^^^                   ^^^^^\n"
"                                    always -1              always 31\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:322
msgid "The converter adds the compiler-supplied constants:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:324
msgid ""
"fn convert_shuffle_i32(op, ctx, intrinsic_name, clamp: i32) {\n"
"    let operands = get_operands(op, ctx)?;\n"
"    let (val, lane_or_delta) = (operands[0], operands[1]);\n"
"\n"
"    let mask_val  = create_i32_const(ctx, -1);   // all 32 lanes "
"participate\n"
"    let clamp_val = create_i32_const(ctx, clamp); // full warp width\n"
"\n"
"    let func_ty = FuncType::get(ctx.ctx, i32_ty.into(),\n"
"        vec![i32_ty, i32_ty, i32_ty, i32_ty], false);\n"
"\n"
"    let call_op = call_intrinsic(ctx, intrinsic_name, func_ty,\n"
"        vec![mask_val, val, lane_or_delta, clamp_val]);\n"
"\n"
"    map_result(op, call_op, ctx);\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:342
msgid ""
"The mask value of `-1` (all bits set) means all 32 lanes in the warp "
"participate. The clamp value of `31` means the shuffle wraps at the full "
"warp width. These are the right defaults for almost every use case, and "
"exposing them to the user would just be noise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:347
msgid "Stage 5 -- Export (Add Convergent)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:349
msgid ""
"Warp shuffles are **convergent** -- LLVM must not reorder them relative to "
"control flow. The export step checks `is_convergent_intrinsic()`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:352
msgid ""
"fn is_convergent_intrinsic(name: &str) -> bool {\n"
"    name == \"llvm.nvvm.barrier0\"\n"
"        || name.starts_with(\"llvm.nvvm.shfl\")      // shuffles\n"
"        || name.starts_with(\"llvm.nvvm.vote\")       // votes\n"
"        || name.starts_with(\"llvm.nvvm.mbarrier\")   // async barriers\n"
"        || name.starts_with(\"llvm.nvvm.cp.async.bulk\")\n"
"        // ...\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:363
msgid ""
"If your new intrinsic is convergent, add it here. If you forget, LLVM might "
"hoist it out of an `if` block, and your warp-level code will produce wrong "
"results or deadlock. Not great."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:369
msgid ""
"declare i32 @llvm.nvvm.shfl.sync.bfly.i32(i32, i32, i32, i32)\n"
"\n"
"%v8 = call i32 @llvm.nvvm.shfl.sync.bfly.i32(\n"
"    i32 -1, i32 %v3, i32 %v4, i32 31) #0\n"
"\n"
"attributes #0 = { convergent }\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:380
msgid "shfl.sync.bfly.b32  %r3, %r1, %r2, 31;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:386
msgid "The Inline PTX Path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:388
msgid ""
"Some operations do not have LLVM intrinsics. For those, we emit inline PTX "
"assembly directly. The helper `inline_asm_convergent()` handles the "
"boilerplate:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:391
msgid ""
"// wgmma fence: no inputs, no outputs, just a side effect\n"
"inline_asm_convergent(\n"
"    ctx, void_ty.into(), vec![],\n"
"    \"wgmma.fence.sync.aligned;\", \"\"\n"
");\n"
"\n"
"// mbarrier arrive: one input (pointer), one output (token)\n"
"inline_asm_convergent(\n"
"    ctx, i64_ty.into(), vec![ptr_val],\n"
"    \"mbarrier.arrive.shared.b64 $0, [$1];\", \"=l,r\"\n"
");\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:405
msgid "The constraint string follows LLVM inline assembly syntax:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "Constraint"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "Meaning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "`=l`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "Output: 64-bit register"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "`=r`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "Output: 32-bit register"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "`r`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "Input: 32-bit register"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "`l`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "Input: 64-bit register"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "(empty)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:179
msgid "No inputs or outputs (side-effect only)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:415
msgid ""
"The `sideeffect convergent` markers on the inline assembly tell LLVM to "
"leave it alone -- do not move it, do not delete it, do not duplicate it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:420
msgid "End-to-End: The Full Journey"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:422
msgid ""
"Here is every representation `threadIdx_x` passes through, top to bottom:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:424
msgid ""
"Rust:         thread::threadIdx_x()\n"
"MIR:          _3 = threadIdx_x() -> bb1\n"
"Pliron MIR:   %v = nvvm.read_ptx_sreg_tid_x : i32\n"
"Pliron LLVM:  %v = call i32 @llvm_nvvm_read_ptx_sreg_tid_x()\n"
"LLVM IR:      %v5 = call i32 @llvm.nvvm.read.ptx.sreg.tid.x()\n"
"PTX:          mov.u32 %r1, %tid.x;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:433
msgid "And `shuffle_xor`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:435
msgid ""
"Rust:         warp::shuffle_xor(val, mask)\n"
"MIR:          _5 = shuffle_xor(_3, _4) -> bb2\n"
"Pliron MIR:   %v = nvvm.shfl_sync_bfly_i32 %val, %mask : i32\n"
"Pliron LLVM:  %v = call i32 @llvm_nvvm_shfl_sync_bfly_i32(i32 -1, %val, "
"%mask, i32 31)\n"
"LLVM IR:      %v8 = call i32 @llvm.nvvm.shfl.sync.bfly.i32(i32 -1, %v3, %v4, "
"i32 31) #0\n"
"PTX:          shfl.sync.bfly.b32 %r3, %r1, %r2, 31;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/adding-new-intrinsics.md:444
msgid ""
"Six representations. One Rust function call becomes one PTX instruction. The "
"intermediate steps exist so that each transformation is small, verifiable, "
"and independently testable."
msgstr ""

